{"title":"Lenovo laptop’s rollable screen uses motors to grow from 14 to 16.7 inches","link":"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2025/01/lenovo-laptop-has-a-screen-that-expands-from-14-to-16-7-inches-for-3500/","date":1736276882000,"content":"<p>Lenovo announced a laptop today that experiments with a new way to offer laptop users more screen space than the typical clamshell design. The Lenovo ThinkBook Plus Gen 6 Rollable has a screen that can roll up vertically to expand from 14 inches diagonally to 16.7 inches, presenting an alternative to prior foldable-screen and dual-screen laptops.</p>\n<figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"1016\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/05_ThinkBook_Plus_6_Rear_Left_Screen_90_Degrees_Rolled_Up-1024x1016.jpeg\" alt=\"Lenovo ThinkBook Plus Gen 6 Rollable\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/05_ThinkBook_Plus_6_Rear_Left_Screen_90_Degrees_Rolled_Up-1024x1016.jpeg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/05_ThinkBook_Plus_6_Rear_Left_Screen_90_Degrees_Rolled_Up-640x635.jpeg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/05_ThinkBook_Plus_6_Rear_Left_Screen_90_Degrees_Rolled_Up-768x762.jpeg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/05_ThinkBook_Plus_6_Rear_Left_Screen_90_Degrees_Rolled_Up-1536x1524.jpeg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/05_ThinkBook_Plus_6_Rear_Left_Screen_90_Degrees_Rolled_Up-980x972.jpeg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/05_ThinkBook_Plus_6_Rear_Left_Screen_90_Degrees_Rolled_Up-1440x1428.jpeg 1440w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/05_ThinkBook_Plus_6_Rear_Left_Screen_90_Degrees_Rolled_Up.jpeg 2000w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      Here you can see the PC's backside when the screen is extended. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Lenovo\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-1024x1024.jpeg\" alt=\"Lenovo ThinkBook Plus Gen 6 Rollable\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-1024x1024.jpeg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-640x640.jpeg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-300x300.jpeg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-768x768.jpeg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-1536x1536.jpeg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-500x500.jpeg 500w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-1000x1000.jpeg 1000w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-980x980.jpeg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge-1440x1440.jpeg 1440w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/hinge.jpeg 2000w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      A look at the hinge. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Lenovo\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"Lenovo ThinkBook Plus Gen 6 Rollable\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-1024x1024.jpg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-640x640.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-300x300.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-768x768.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-500x500.jpg 500w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-1000x1000.jpg 1000w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-980x980.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard-1440x1440.jpg 1440w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/keyboard.jpg 2000w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      The keyboard includes a button for making the screen unroll. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Lenovo\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n  \n<p>The laptop, which Lenovo says is coming out in June, builds on <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2023/02/lenovo-demos-laptop-that-rolls-from-13-to-15-inches-with-the-flip-of-a-switch/?preview_id=1920286&amp;preview_nonce=b168769eb6&amp;_thumbnail_id=1920376&amp;preview=true\">a concept that Lenovo demoed </a>in February 2023. That prototype had a Sharp-made panel that initially measured 12.7 inches but could unroll to present a total screen size of 15.3 inches. Lenovo's final product is working with a bigger display from Samsung Display, <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2025/1/7/24337633/lenovo-thinkbook-plus-gen-6-rollable-laptop-flexible-oled-price-specs\">The Verge</a> reported. Resolution-wise you're going from 2,000×1,600 pixels (about 183 pixels per inch) to 2,000×2,350 (184.8 ppi), the publication said.</p>\n<p>Users make the screen expand by pressing a dedicated button on the keyboard or by making a hand gesture at the PC's webcam. Expansion entails about 10 seconds of loud whirring from the laptop’s motors. Lenovo executives told The Verge that the laptop was rated for at least 20,000 rolls up and down and 30,000 hinge openings and closings.</p><p><a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2025/01/lenovo-laptop-has-a-screen-that-expands-from-14-to-16-7-inches-for-3500/\">Read full article</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2025/01/lenovo-laptop-has-a-screen-that-expands-from-14-to-16-7-inches-for-3500/#comments\">Comments</a></p>","author":"Scharon Harding","siteTitle":"Ars Technica","siteHash":"5b0ddf6e8923e49262a7894cfd77962733e43fbcc565a103b48373820b310636","entryHash":"300083aa81378f750aab83c223d89d35367e0835158dc4223542a802d7eda696","category":"Tech"}